metadata.name: CA Panico RGB #106
metadata.description:
Another tribute to Stephen Wolfram and his cellular automata, that's a reworking of my previous CA Panico collection.

In this version the RGB basic colors reign supreme, every single color is set by a cellular automata formula, giving life to interesting and particular textures and patterns.

Press 'S' to download.

metadata.description:
"To capture the fleeting time in the generating process."

In this work,I d'like focus on the generating of generative art system itself rather than imitate some scene or style.
And with the flow of time, try to figure out where it can take me toward.

This work would be a series of my alternative view on generative art.

metadata.name: Eternal Shards #7
metadata.description: In the void between time and memory, there exists a realm where fragments of forgotten lives drift in silent harmony. These Eternal Shards‚Äîcrystalline echoes of joy, sorrow, and stillness‚Äîhover in a delicate balance, bound by threads of light that pulse with the weight of what once was. Some glow fiercely as if resisting their inevitable fade; others stand dormant, their edges dulled by the erosion of years. Scattered across this boundless expanse, they form constellations of meaning‚Äîdense clusters of shared moments, sparse trails of solitary thoughts, or tangled webs of intertwined fates. A wanderer who stumbles into this space might see their own past reflected in the shards‚Äô silent dance, a mosaic of what endures and what slips away, forever caught in a single, unshifting breath.

metadata.name: System Œ≤ #222
metadata.description:
Œ± -> Œ≤ is about "Increases in magnitude and decreases in computation". And still related the fleeting time in the generating process.

My role in this work is more of a discoverer than a creator. 

Try to reveal the possibilities of time perception in the generative art through negotiating with incomprehensible mathematical equations.

What I want to explore through this work is that behind the generated results, the dynamic process of generations are equally diverse and unpredictable.

When we watch the generating process displayed on the computer, changing instantly, moving, multiplying, disappearing, and we hesitate, wonder, pause, await, as if many possibilities of time perception have emerged in the fragmented moments.

metadata.name: Illuminations #211
metadata.description:
Created for the FxHash Turns One week - Thank you FxHash for all the opportunities you have given generative artists and collectors, and thank you to everyone who makes, and collects, the great art here. Here are a few celebratory generative effects which come from my 2022 experiments on random walks through color and space.

There are 5 different burst patterns (Whirligig, Sky Ripple, Confetti, Classic, Sparkler) and the Cocktail type brings them all together (somewhat chaotically)

To continue with the display after it stops press c

To switch to tranquil mode press t - You will want to try this out when you have a minute

To switch back to live mode press v

To stop the display process press x

To save a 2800x2800 jpg press s

Made with p5.js - all proceeds and royalties assigned to the Processing Foundation (who also deserve a big thank you)

This work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International License.

metadata.name: Bindu #27
metadata.description:
The series employs fractal circles to create repeating patterns, using a monochrome color palette on the canvas. The number, size, and density of circles as well as the level of recursion, vary across pieces. The introduction of these variations and arcs adds a new dimension to fractals by juxtaposing their self-similar nature at all scales with elements of randomness.

This is my third series in a row that features a monochromatic color palette. There's something about the limitation of using only binary colors that enables me to appreciate abstraction purely for its form.

Note on the name: The series draws its name from Sayed Haider Raza of the Bombay Progressive Artists' Group. I have always admired Raza‚Äôs use of sacred geometry and his abstract work has forever been a source of inspiration. Raza believed that ‚ÄòBindu‚Äô (the dot, point or circle) is the ultimate point of creation, representing the universe in its entirety.

Implemented in JS, this code utilizes the Perlin.js and Simple-noise.js libraries.

Press p to save a png of the image in full screen. Press s to save an svg file.

Pixel Love!
